    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-01-09T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-01-09T16:00:00-05:00" n="544"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d544">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.00/6109: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morris</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="32" xml:id="d544fn32">The same, except the first sentence,
                        to the Ambassador in Great Britain as no. 19, with instructions to
                        “Communicate following to Foreign Office and repeat to Paris, Rome and
                        Prague for similar action.”</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-01-09T16:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 9, 1920—4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>7. Repeat following to Legation Peking, to Harris and to Consul Vladivostok to be
                    given by him to Smith, Stevens, and Graves. It will be released to press at
                    Washington Tuesday January 13th.<note n="33" xml:id="d544fn33">The memorandum
                        was released to the press Jan. 16.</note>
                </p>
                <pb facs="0591" n="491" xml:id="pg_491"/>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“On December 8, 1919, the Japanese Ambassador at Washington, pursuant to
                        instructions from his Government, invited the attention of the Secretary of
                            State<note n="34" xml:id="d544fn34">Memorandum not printed.</note> to
                        the recent unfavorable development of the situation in Siberia, and inquired
                        whether the United States proposed to maintain the <hi rend="italic">status
                            quo</hi>, or to proceed to entire or partial withdrawal of its troops,
                        or whether it was ready to send reenforcements in case of need.</p>
                    <p>“The Secretary of State has today communicated to the Japanese Ambassador the
                        decision of the Government of the United States in the following
                        memorandum:</p>
                    <p>[Here follows memorandum printed on <ref target="#pg_487">page
                        487</ref>.]</p>
                </quote>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
